shire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1242–1289":"1242–1289","–Male":"Deceased","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1189–Male":"1189–Deceased","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1270":"about 1270","1242":"1242","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1289":"1289","1245":"1245","1189":"1189","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","about 1245":"about 1245","about 1242":"about 1242","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rishton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rushton  . Early bearers: Aleander Rishton, 1560 in   IGI   (Great Harwood, Lancs); Anna Rishton, 1598, Elizabeth Rushton, 1635 in   IGI   (Altham, Lancs); Robert Rishton, 1603, James Rushton, 1627, Robert Riston, 1757 in   IGI   (Colne, Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rushton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rishton (Lancashire) and Rushton (Staffordshire), and perhaps also from Rushton (Cheshire, Northamptonshire), Rushton in East Stoke (Dorset), and Rhiston (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>risc</i> ‘rush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["1  English: (i) perhaps a variant of   Garth   with loss of  <i>-r-</i> before the final consonant. Compare Thomas Gath, 1600, John Garth, 1619 in   IGI   (Saint Keyne, Cornwall); Nicholas Gath, 1716, Thomas Garth, 1726 in   IGI   (Saint Breward, Cornwall). (ii) alternatively, a variant of   Goth   with unrounding of the vowel, if not vice versa.","2  Irish: from  <b>Mag Eochadha</b>,  see  McGough  ."]},{"name":"Riston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":17,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Rishton was born in 1242, in Rishton, Lancashire, England, Unite